<HEADLINE>
<P>
DR. NEIL SOLOMON: ACNE AND WASHING UP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By NEIL SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: If a teen-ager has an acne condition, how important is it that the 
face be washed? I have known adolescents who were far from clean and who were 
never bothered with acne, and I have known others who appeared to be very clean 
who had a bad condition. How important is cleanliness in this? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: I recommend patients with acne wash two or three times day, using a 
mild soap and water; however, scrubbing the skin is not recommended. Acne is 
not caused by dirt. Scrubbing the skin will not improve the condition, and may 
even tend to aggravate it. 
</P>
<P>
If you have a medical question, write to Dr. Solomon, P.O. Box 36184, 
Baltimore, Md. 21285-6184. Solomon cannot give personal replies but will answer 
as many questions as possible in his column. 
</P>
</TEXT>
