<P>
MILITARY KEEPS GRIP DESPITE VOTE LOSS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Although the military government of Myanmar now officially recognizes that the 
opposition won recent elections, it has shown few signs of turning over real 
power, diplomats in Yangon, the capital of what was formerly Burma, said. On 
Sunday, the regime announced the last result in the May 27 election for a new 
national assembly, confirming a landslide victory for the opposition National 
League for Democracy. The junta had promised to hand over power after the 
multi-party elections, but "the military is proceeding as if the elections 
never took place," said one diplomat. 
</P>
