<HEADLINE>
<P>
MILLION-DOLLAR VIEW COMES CHEAP IN CITY-OWNED OCEAN BLUFF HOUSES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TIM WATERS, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The term subsidized housing has taken on a new meaning in upscale Palos Verdes 
Estates. 
</P>
<P>
Just ask Jim Hendrickson, who became the community's city manager last fall 
with a contract that allows him to live rent-free in a bluff-top house with 
post-card views of the ocean. 
</P>
<P>
"It's just amazing to sit in the living room and all you see is the ocean," 
Hendrickson said. 
</P>
<P>
If Hendrickson stumbled onto a good deal, so did two city police officers who 
live on the same street. Their houses also are on the bluffs and have ocean 
views. The officers don't get free rent, but their contract with the city calls 
for them to make only $400 worth of improvements to their houses each month. 
</P>
<P>
The good housing deals have come about because of a dozen lawsuits filed 
against the city over the past decade. Residents of Palos Verdes Drive West, in 
an area known as Bluff Cove, contended that their properties were undermined by 
water from a faulty city storm drain. 
</P>
<P>
Although the city has vigorously defended itself, it has nevertheless found 
itself the reluctant owner of six houses. Three are occupied by the city 
employees. The city later will take possession of the other three under the 
terms of various legal settlements. 
</P>
<P>
Of the remaining six houses involved in the lawsuits, the city could wind up 
owning two more, depending on the outcome of litigation. Three were razed 
because they were uninhabitable, and another was kept by the owners as part of 
their legal settlement. 
</P>
<P>
City officials maintain that the three houses occupied by the employees are 
safe to live in, even though 20 to 30 feet of Hendrickson's back yard long ago 
fell over a cliff and into the ocean. The city's assurances notwithstanding, 
the houses sat vacant and became popular hangouts for transients and revelers 
until four years ago. That's when the two police officers inquired about living 
in them. 
</P>
<P>
City Council members, seeing a way to upgrade, maintain and provide security 
for the houses -- and provide housing for employees who otherwise could not 
afford to live in the city -- went along with the idea. 
</P>
<P>
"We're making the best out of a bad situation," Councilwoman Ruth Gralow said. 
</P>
<P>
In Hendrickson's case, the city evicted a police officer who had lived in the 
house for two years and offered it to him rent-free, providing he would accept 
a salary lower than he would make elsewhere. Hendrickson agreed to accept 
$65,000 a year, a good $15,000 to $20,000 less than the city would have had to 
pay otherwise, Gralow said. 
</P>
<P>
Hendrickson said he has put $11,800 of his money into fixing up the house, 
installing new plumbing, carpets, blinds and wallpaper. With the rent-free 
house came a clause in his contract requiring him to be available around the 
clock. A direct telephone line to the Police Department has been installed in 
the house, he said. 
</P>
<P>
"I've told a number of people I am never going to live in as nice a home 
again," said Hendrickson, who was formerly San Clemente's city manager. 
</P>
<P>
Dave Black, one of the two police officers who initially approached the city 
about living in the residences, said his house was a "basic fixer-upper" when 
he moved into it. Because he was a construction worker before he became a 
police officer, he had the skills to do the work himself, he said. 
</P>
<P>
Detective Darin Kasten, who lives next door to Black, said his house sat vacant 
for seven years before he moved in. The windows had all been broken and the 
floors destroyed, he said. 
</P>
<P>
"It was just like an open shell," Kasten said. 
</P>
<P>
Under their contracts with the city, Hendrickson and the officers have agreed 
not to hold the city liable should the land become unstable. All three said 
they do not worry about that happening. 
</P>
<P>
And although Hendrickson will not be forced to move as long as he is city 
manager, no such security is offered to the police officers. Their housing 
contracts with the city can be canceled any month. 
</P>
<P>
Indeed, some city officials have suggested that the houses, situated in a 
neighborhood where dwellings easily sell for seven figures, could be used to 
entice other top administrators to the city. But if that happens, Black said, 
he will have no regrets. 
</P>
<P>
"If they asked me to leave tomorrow, I would be happy because I have had four 
good years." 
</P>
</TEXT>
