<P>
JAPANESE CLUB DISBANDS AFTER U.S. COMPLAINTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TOKYO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Executives of Japanese building firms have disbanded a social club to help meet 
U.S. demands for an end to bid rigging in the local construction industry, 
company spokesmen said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
The 32-member club had met monthly since 1983. 
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials had voiced suspicions that the meetings, which were closed to 
outsiders, may have included discussions to assign projects to specific 
contractors. 
</P>
<P>
The club was disbanded after seven leading members decided to withdraw, the 
Asahi Shimbun national daily reported. 
