<P>
JAPAN PLEDGES HELP, PRESIDENT-ELECT SAYS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President-elect Alberto Fujimori won a round in his battle to reopen the 
foreign aid flow by securing Japan's pledge to send an economic cooperation 
mission to Peru. "Mr. Kaifu clearly understood our economic problems," Fujimori 
told reporters in Tokyo after meeting Japanese Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu. 
Japanese officials said Kaifu also promised to send a group of economic 
advisers to help the Lima government draw up a retrenchment strategy. The 
Japanese economic experts will go to Lima after Fujimori's inauguration July 
28. 
</P>
