<P>
GOLF STORY WAS A FISH TALE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Service 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
KENNEBUNKPORT, Me. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It was apparently just a typical case of trying to make the boss look good when 
expert golfer Dan Quayle spread the word that President Bush had beat him on 
the links. 
</P>
<P>
"He was just being pleasant, I'll bet," Bush said of his vice president today. 
</P>
<P>
Quayle somewhat sheepishly told reporters. "He won on the first tee." 
</P>
<P>
"Won one hole. That's what he meant," Bush clarified. 
</P>
<P>
Quayle had told reporters on Monday when setting out to golf near Bush's 
seaside vacation home that he was "destined to lose." 
</P>
<P>
Quayle is renowned in Washington for his expertise on the golf course. Bush on 
the other hand, is trying to improve his somewhat ragged game. 
</P>
<P>
When asked later Monday who won the game at the Cape Arundel Golf Course, 
Quayle said, "The President won." Suspicion was widespread that he was speaking 
tongue in cheek. 
</P>
